DOCUMENT();

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "parserPopUp.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
           );

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,29,1);
$b = random(1.09,1.35,.01);
$r = ($b-1)*100;
$dec_r = $b-1;
$k = round(log($b)/log(exp(1))*10000)/10000;
$cont = round(log($b)/log(exp(1))*10000)/100;

$popup = PopUp(["?","growth", "decay"],"growth");

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Write the exponential function \( y = $a ($b)^{t} \)
in the form \( y = ae^{kt} \).
$PAR
(a) Once you have rewritten the formula, give \(k\) accurate
to at least four decimal places.
$BR
\( \ k = \) \{ ans_rule(15) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$PAR
If \(t\) is measured in years, indicate whether the exponential
function is growing or decaying and find the annual and continuous
growth/decay rates.  The rates you determine should be positive in
the case of growth or decay (by choosing decay the negative rate
is implied).
$PAR
(b) The annual \{ $popup->menu() \} rate is
\{ ans_rule(15) \} $PERCENT per year (round to the nearest 0.01${PERCENT}).
$PAR
(c) The continuous \{ $popup->menu() \} rate is
\{ ans_rule(15) \} $PERCENT per year (round to the nearest 0.01${PERCENT}).

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Real("$k")->cmp(tolerance=>0.0001,tolType=>"absolute") );
#   ANS(num_cmp($k,tol=>0.0001) );

ANS($popup->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$r")->cmp(tolerance=>0.006,tolType=>"absolute") );
#   ANS(num_cmp($r,tol=>0.006) );

ANS($popup->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$cont")->cmp(tolerance=>0.006,tolType=>"absolute") );
#   ANS(num_cmp($cont,tol=>0.006) );


Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR
(a) We want \( $a ($b)^{t} = ae^{kt} \), so we choose \(a = $a\)
and we find \(k\) such that \( e^{k} = $b \).  Taking the natural
log of both sides we find \( k = \ln{($b)} \approx $k \).  Therefore
the given function is equivalent to:
\[ y = $a e^{$k t} \]
$PAR
Notice that because the growth factor \(b > 1\) (or because \(k > 0\))
we have exponential growth.
$PAR
(b) Since \($b-1 = $dec_r\), the annual growth rate is $r$PERCENT per year. $BR
(c) Since \(k = \ln($b) \approx $k\) the continuous growth rate is about
$cont$PERCENT per year.

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;


COMMENT('MathObject version');
